3	What was your data set size?	My dataset consisted of over one million records, which required careful extraction, cleaning, and optimization to maintain dashboard performance.
4	Which mode did you use to connect your data?	I used Import Mode, which loads data into Power BI's in-memory engine, ensuring high performance and responsiveness for my reports.
5	Are you familiar with DAX? What functions did you use?	Yes, I use DAX for calculated measures and KPIs. I primarily use time intelligence functions like MoM and YoY comparisons to analyze trends.
6	Name two aggregation functions.	I use SUMX for row-level dynamic calculations and AVERAGE to calculate the mean value of columns in my reports.
7	Scenarios for SUM and SUMX?	I use SUM for simple column totals and SUMX when I need to perform a calculation on each row (e.g., Qty × Price) before aggregating.
8	Write a DAX query using SUMX.	Total Sales = SUMX(Sales, Sales[Quantity] * Sales[UnitPrice]). It iterates through the table to calculate totals row-by-row before summing.
9	Question on calculated columns?	Yes, I use calculated columns for KPI segmentation and date-based classification when the field is not present in the source data.
10	Scenario for implementing RLS?	I implemented RLS when different business units needed to see only their region-specific data, ensuring privacy and tailored insights.
11	How did you implement RLS?	I defined roles in the Modeling tab, wrote DAX filters for specific columns, and then assigned users/groups to those roles in the Power BI Service.
12	Where do you provide access for RLS?	I assign users or security groups to the specific roles within the Dataset Security Settings in the Power BI Service after publishing.
13	What kind of visuals have you used?	I use bar and column charts for comparisons, line charts for trends, pie charts for proportions, and KPI cards for highlighting key metrics.
14	Difference between slicer and filter?	Slicers are interactive, visible controls on the report canvas for users, while filters are applied behind the scenes via the Filter Pane.
15	Visual vs. Page Level Filters?	Visual-level filters restrict only one specific chart, whereas page-level filters apply to all visuals on that specific report page.
16	What is Power BI Service?	It is a cloud-based platform used to publish, share, and collaborate on reports, enabling scheduled refreshes and secure access from anywhere.
17	Have you worked on report sharing?	Yes, I share reports via secured workspaces and automated email subscriptions to keep stakeholders updated without manual intervention.
18	What ETL tools have you used?	I primarily use SQL for ETL and Power Query within Power BI for data cleaning and transformation, along with Snowflake for cloud storage.
19	Was your source on-premise or cloud?	I have worked with both, using an on-premises SQL Server with a Data Gateway, and connecting directly to Snowflake for cloud-based data.
20	Which gateway did you connect?	I used the On-Premises Data Gateway to act as a secure bridge for refreshing local SQL Server data in the cloud.
21	What was your workspace capacity?	My reports were deployed in a Shared Capacity environment, which is the standard default for most Power BI users.
22	Why check the user license?	It ensures the user has legal access to the BI environment and verifies they have the appropriate rights to view the report content.
